<a href="javascript:card_browser(140)">Hate</a> x4    </FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font class="h2font"> Strategy</Font></TD><TD> </TD></TR><TR><TD COLSPAN="2" VALIGN="TOP"><font class="bfont"> PLEASE READ STRATEGY BEFORE REVIEWING<br />
<br />
The Start:<br />
<br />
You begin by bidding 0.  Whether you go first or second, it makes no difference.  This deck is strong in either situation.  If you go first, you can use your wound redistribution and continuous healing to keep your companions alive as you move along.  However, a more ideal situation is that you go second, which will usually be the case.  You won’t get the Prancing Pony (unless your opponent starts it), but the rest of your sites will come out, but moreover, your opponent will have to move through your shadow, which is a direct damage machine.  This deck can get the job done . . . however, it does have some weaknesses, which is why this is listed as a fun deck.  I’ll get to those in a minute.  First . . . <br />
<br />
The Adventure Path:<br />
<br />
Prancing Pony:  Probably won’t get to play yours, but if you do, you get to get Aragorn.  If you don’t see it, there are 4 Aragorns in the deck, so don’t worry.<br />
Midgewater Marsh:  You make your opponents hobbits exert.  That’s as good as direct damage.<br />
Rivendell Waterfall:  I’m just trying to entice my opponent to make the ill-advised triple move.<br />
Dwarrowdelf Chamber:  I hardly ever see decks that play Gimli, so this site deals two wounds to my opponent’s fellowship.<br />
The Bridge:  Khazad-dum bridge is falling down, falling down, falling down . . . <br />
Galadriel’s Glade:  Not a forest.  No A Ranger’s Versatility here.<br />
Silverlode Banks:  It’s quite possible that I’ve killed a Ranger or two by now.  If so, everybody exerts.  More direct damage for me.<br />
Shores of Nen Hithoel:  9 twilight.  I’m playing orcs.  This is a no-brainer.<br />
Tol Brandir: By now, I may well have killed off two characters.  Therefore, 3 trackers plus whatever is in my hand should overwhelm the ring-bearer with ease.<br />
<br />
The Fellowship:<br />
<br />
I start Gimli and Arwen, my Shoulder to Shoulder platform.  With them, I can relocate wounds from Gimli to Arwen so that he can continue to exert and win skirmishes.  Meanwhile, Aragorn removes those wounds one at a time.  And 4 Aragorns says I will get him quickly.  And if I don’t get him off the bat, I should have one of my 3 Boromirs to help me along.  Try and end every turn with a wound on Boromir or Arwen, because Aragorn will heal it.  Basically, this deck is all about survival because with my shadow, the opposing fellowship can’t survive, so I’ve just got to give my shadow an opportunity to work.  <br />
<br />
The Shadow:<br />
<br />
The Adventure Path; 4 scouting bands, 4 war bands, 4 Hates, 4 Bowmen, 4 Watching Eyes!  All of these things add wounds.  I don’t care where they go, just so long as they go somewhere, because eventually, the wounds will add up big time!  And then by site 7, 8, and 9, companions start dying.  Things have gotten too severe.  Finally, the average 5 companion fellowship arrives at site 9 having lost 2 companions to direct damage.  3 trackers arrive from the discard pile plus two orcs from my hand, the opposing fellowship takes more bowmen wounds, and I overwhelm the ring-bearer.  All of this wound distribution got this deck it’s name (that and my Hobbits on Wallstreet article).<br />
<br />
The Weaknesses:<br />
<br />
Like I said, the deck was built for fun, even though it can be very competitive.  The reason why I do NOT consider this deck tournament worthy is because of its glaring weakness—Gandalf.  Without a stronger fellowship (which is to say a more standard archery fellowship), I can’t really afford to move quickly.  I am forced to let my shadow do all of the talking.  But against a good Gandalf deck, my Shadow is impotent.  Sleep, Caradhras is just devastating enough to completely undermine my entire deck.  Now with a stronger fellowship, I could race to site 9, but this fellowship is designed only to give my shadow a chance.  It is not strong enough to race against Nazgul.  Hence, the deck has a glaring weakness and is just for fun.<br />
<br />
Thanks for the read!  Enjoy!<br />
<br />
Devon &quot;Devonator&quot; Clark </FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP" COLSPAN="2"><font class="bfont"> <a href="/lotr/decks/decks.php?PHPSESSID=aeaa9672b866240c1054c7e429b04ccf">Back to Decks Directory</a> | <A HREF="/lotr/decks/decks.php?reviews=21629&PHPSESSID=aeaa9672b866240c1054c7e429b04ccf"> Read Reviews </A> | <a href="deckprint.php?deck=21629&PHPSESSID=aeaa9672b866240c1054c7e429b04ccf" TARGET="BLANK_"> Printer Friendly</a></FONT></TD></TR></TABLE><a name="review"></a><font class="h2font">In order to review decks you must be a registered member. <A href="/lotr/main/join.php?PHPSESSID=aeaa9672b866240c1054c7e429b04ccf">Sign up for free!</A></font></font></td><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_09.gif"></td></tr>
